---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Highcharts GenAI Evaluation Framework"
  description="An offline LLM-as-judge evaluation framework for AI-generated Highcharts configs in QuickSight."
>
  <article class="p-6 lg:p-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <a
      href="/shipped"
      class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-charcoal-muted dark:text-sand-muted
             hover:text-accent dark:hover:text-accent-light transition-colors mb-8"
    >
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M7 16l-4-4m0 0l4-4m-4 4h18" />
      </svg>
      Back to shipped work
    </a>

    <header class="mb-10">
      <div class="case-cover mb-8" aria-label="Cover image placeholder">
        <span>Cover image</span>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm text-accent dark:text-accent-light font-medium mb-4 tracking-wide uppercase">
        Amazon Web Services · QuickSight
      </p>

      <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold text-balance leading-tight">
        Highcharts GenAI Evaluation Framework
      </h1>

      <p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-charcoal-muted dark:text-sand-muted">
        I built an offline evaluation framework for AI-generated Highcharts configurations,
        using an LLM-as-judge architecture to compare prompts, models, and chart-generation strategies.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-lg dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>Problem</h2>
      <p>
        QuickSight had a use case where a user could describe a chart in natural language and the
        system would produce a Highcharts configuration. The hard part was evaluating whether changes
        to system prompts, models, or generation strategies actually improved chart quality.
      </p>

      <p>
        The evaluation system needed to work offline, run across a benchmark set, and support cases
        where a known-good reference existed as well as cases where the generated chart had to be judged
        without a reference answer.
      </p>

      <h2>What I Built</h2>
      <p>
        I created a benchmark-driven evaluation framework where each chart-generation strategy runs
        against each benchmark case. The framework orchestrates those runs concurrently, captures the
        generated Highcharts configs, and sends the results through evaluation flows.
      </p>

      <p>
        The system supported both reference-based evaluation, where generated output could be compared
        against an expected chart, and reference-free evaluation, where an LLM judge evaluated whether
        the rendered chart satisfied the user intent.
      </p>

      <h2>Browser-Based Judging</h2>
      <p>
        Because chart quality is visual, the framework did not stop at inspecting JSON. I added a path
        to spin up Playwright sessions, render generated Highcharts outputs in the browser, and use that
        rendered result as part of the judging loop.
      </p>

      <h2>Impact</h2>
      <p>
        The framework made it possible to evaluate model and prompt changes against a repeatable set of
        chart-generation benchmarks instead of relying on manual spot checks. It gave the team a way to
        compare strategies across the same workload and reason about regressions or improvements before
        shipping changes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .case-cover {
    display: grid;
    min-height: 18rem;
    place-items: center;
    border: 1px solid rgb(232 224 208);
    border-radius: 0.5rem;
    background:
      linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(47, 111, 159, 0.2) 25%, transparent 25%) 0 0 / 24px 24px,
      linear-gradient(135deg, transparent 75%, rgba(47, 111, 159, 0.16) 75%) 0 0 / 24px 24px,
      rgb(245 240 232);
  }

  :global(.dark) .case-cover {
    border-color: rgb(37 36 34);
    background:
      linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(59, 126, 161, 0.24) 25%, transparent 25%) 0 0 / 24px 24px,
      linear-gradient(135deg, transparent 75%, rgba(59, 126, 161, 0.18) 75%) 0 0 / 24px 24px,
      rgb(37 36 34);
  }

  .case-cover span {
    font-family: "JetBrains Mono", monospace;
    color: rgb(74 74 74);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  }

  :global(.dark) .case-cover span {
    color: rgb(184 180 172);
  }
</style>
